{{distinguish|George Lockhart (disambiguation)}}
{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2017}}
{{Use British English|date=March 2017}}
'''George Lokert''' of [[Ayr]] (c. 1485 &ndash; 1547) was a Scottish philosopher and theologian who made significant contributions to the study of [[logic]]. A pupil of [[John Major (philosopher)|John Mair]], he also studied and taught at the University of Paris, and eventually served as prior of [[the Sorbonne]]. Returning to Scotland in 1521, he served as [[Rector of the University of St Andrews]] (1522-5).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scottishphilosophy.org/georgelokert.html|title=George Lokert ?1485-1547|publisher=International Association for Scottish Philosophy|accessdate=3 January 2011}}</ref>

Returning to Paris, he was closely associated with [[Noël Béda]].

After his second period in Paris, Lokert served as the provost of Crichton, and dean of the [[University of Glasgow]].

